SIMPLE: hocus-pocus
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hocus-pocus
<hw>Ho"cus-po"cus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. invented
by jugglers in imitation of Latin. Cf. <er>Hoax</er>,
<er>Hocus</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A term used by magicians or
conjurers in pretended incantations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A juggler or trickster.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir T. Herbert.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A magician's trick; a cheat; nonsense.</def>
<rj><au>Hudibras.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Obfuscating talk or elaborate but meaningless
activity intended to hide a deception or to obscure what is actually
happening; verbal misrepresentation intended to take advantage of you in
some way.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> trickery, slickness, hanky panky, jiggery-pokery,
skulduggery, skullduggery.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hocus-pocus</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hocus-pocus
<hw>Ho"cus-po"cus</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cheat.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hod</ent>⟦br⟧
